{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"685bb5fc-fec2-4db5-a37c-4937a38c8170","content":"In .NET MAUI, override the `CreateWindow` method in your `App` class and subscribe to the window lifecycle events:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Lifecycle flow:**\n\n| Transition | Event |\n|---|---|\n| App launches | `Created` → `Activated` |\n| App goes to background | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` |\n| App returns to foreground | `Resumed` → `Activated` |\n| App closes | `Destroying` |\n\n> `Backgrounding` is iOS/Mac Catalyst–specific and provides a state restoration opportunity via `e.State`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0e4bf286-be1c-4462-af40-f4b42f05c5a6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about subscribing to Window lifecycle events in a .NET MAUI app for debugging/logging purposes. This is a general .NET MAUI knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":401,"requestId":"9439:11529C:13C1043:162A78D:6A067051"},"id":"336f4214-dddc-489e-a70d-db4d75f6be8b","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:01:13.541Z","parentId":"c1e80d61-0749-4668-a1cc-441ea2243bcf"}
